==Dutch==
{{wp|lang=nl|Meid (persoon)}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|nl|dum|meit}}, variant of {{m|dum|meget}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|*megith}}, {{m|odt|*magath}}, from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*magaþs}}. Compare also {{m|nl|maagd}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/mɛi̯t/|lang=nl}}
* {{audio|Nl-meid.ogg|Audio|lang=nl}}
* {{hyphenation|lang=nl|meid}}
* {{rhyme|lang=nl|ɛi̯t}}

===Noun===
{{nl-noun|f|-en|meisje|dim2=meidje}}

# [[girl]], [[lass]]
#:{{ux|nl|De '''meiden''' hadden afgelopen zaterdag een zwemwedstrijd.|The '''girls''' had a swimming match last Saturday.}}
#:{{ux|nl|Goed gedaan, '''meid'''!|Well done, '''girl'''!|inline=1}}
# [[maid]]
#: {{syn|nl|bode|deerne|dienstbode|dienstmaagd}}
# {{n-g|Commonly used as an address for female pets, especially female dogs.}}
#:{{ux|nl|Brave '''meid'''!|Good '''girl'''!|inline=1}}

====Usage notes====
* Use in the singular may connote fortitude, bravery or acting like a grown-up, but it may also connote vulgarity or subservience due to the meaning “maid”. These connotations are much weaker in the plural, which can be used neutrally with little regard for context.
* Use for adult women (and to a lesser degree for older adolescent girls) is often considered patronising, which is especially true of the diminutives.
* The diminutive "meidje" is uncommon.

